 bodies, and natural resources is mirrored today in this new era of pervasive datafication. Apps, platforms, and smart objects capture and translate our lives into data, and then extract information that is fed into capitalist enterprises and sold back to us. The authors argue that this development foreshadows the creation of a new social order emerging globally—and it must be challenged. Confronting the alarming degree of surveillance already tolerated, they offer a stirring call to decolonize the internet and emancipate our desire for connection.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aCapitalismxSocial aspects. 0aCapitalism. 0aElectronic data processingxSocial aspects. 0aElectronic data processing. 0aInformation technologyxSocial aspects. 0aInformation technology. 0aInternetxSocial aspects. 0aInternet. 0aSocial sciences. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Media Studies.2bisacsh  aautonomy.  acapitalism.  acolonialism.  aconnection.  adata.  adecoloniality.  aextraction.  ainternet.  apostcolonialism.  asociety.1 aMejias, Ulises A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Social Sciences 2020 Englishz978311070472308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Sociology, Education, Psychology 2020z9783110704549oZDB-23-SEW08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311069228040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150360975440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503609754423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781503609754.jpg  a978-3-11-069228-0  SUP 